candidate_text: The energy density of ethanol is approximately 29.7 megajoules per liter (MJ/L).
The energy content of ethanol is typically measured in megajoules per liter (MJ/L).

The energy content of 1 liter (L) of ethanol is approximately:

* Lower heating value (LHV): 21,113 kilojoules per liter (kJ/L)
* Higher heating value (HHV): 23,444 kJ/L

To convert these values to joules, to get the total number of joules in 1 liter of ethanol, you can multiply by 1000 (since there are 1000 joules in 1 kilojoule).

So,

* LHV: 21,113 kJ/L × 1000 = 21,113,000 J/L ≈ 21.11 MJ/L (megajoules per liter)
* HHV: 23,444 kJ/L × 1000 = 23,444,000 J/L ≈ 23.44 MJ/L (megajoules per liter)

Keep in mind that the exact energy content may vary slightly depending on the specific type and purity of the ethanol.
